Wash and dry all produce. Preheat broiler to high or oven to 500 degrees. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @yellow onion{1/2}(halved, peeled, and thinly sliced) (use the other half as you like). Strip @thyme{1/4%ounce}(leaves stripped from stems) leaves from stems; discard stems.

Melt @butter{1%tbsp} in a large #pan{} over medium heat (use an #ovenproof pan{} if you have one). Add thyme and onion. Cook until softened, ~{5-6%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Pour in @veggie stock concentrate{1} and 1 cup water and bring to a simmer.

Once stock mixture is simmering, add @spinach and ricotta ravioli{9%ounce} to pan. Cover and cook ~{4%minutes}. Uncover and increase heat to high. Continue cooking, spooning stock over ravioli, until ravioli are tender and stock has reduced, ~{5-6%minutes}. Shake pan occasionally to keep ravioli from sticking.

Combine @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup}, @parmesan cheese{1/4%cup}, a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tsp}, and a pinch of salt and pepper in a small #bowl{}.

Remove pan from heat. Carefully stir @sour cream{4%tbsp} and @spinach{5%ounce} into pan until thoroughly combined and spinach is wilted. Season with salt and pepper.

> TIP: Add up to ½ cup water if sauce seems very thick.

If your pan is not ovenproof, transfer mixture to a #baking dish{} at this point.

Sprinkle ravioli in pan (or dish) with crust mixture. Place under broiler and broil until golden brown, ~{1-2%minutes}. Divide between plates and serve.